== Anchors == <!--T:253-->

=== Linking to an anchor === <!--T:254-->
</translate>
<translate><!--T:255--> Links in the format <tvar name=1><code><nowiki>[[#anchor_name]]</nowiki></code></tvar> will direct to the first matching anchor on the page, typically corresponding to the first identical section heading.</translate>

<translate><!--T:256--> You can add an <tvar name=1><code><nowiki>[[#anchor_name]]</nowiki></code></tvar> to a link, directing it to the first matching section heading (or anchor) on the '''named''' page:</translate>

<code><nowiki>[[Help:Editing#Advanced editing]]</nowiki></code>

<code><nowiki>https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Help:Editing#Advanced_editing</nowiki></code>

<translate>
=== Using an automatic anchor === <!--T:257-->
</translate>
<translate><!--T:258--> Section headings serve as anchors, using the heading text as the anchor name.</translate>
<translate><!--T:259--> If there are multiple sections with identical headings, each subsequent occurrence is appended with <tvar name=1>"_2", "_3"</tvar>, etc.</translate>

<translate>
<!--T:260-->
The anchor <tvar name=1>[[#toc]]</tvar> links to the page's table of contents (TOC), except when there's a section already titled <tvar name=2>"toc"</tvar>.

=== A manual anchor === <!--T:261-->
</translate>
<translate><!--T:262--> Manually-set anchors are beneficial for linking to "unlinkable" elements such as tables (titles or cells) or sections of plain text.</translate>
<translate><!--T:263--> For instance, in the [[<tvar name=1>#External links to internal pages</tvar>|External links to internal pages]] section above, although the column text "Description" resembles a (minor) heading, it is not.</translate>

<translate><!--T:264--> There are several methods to set an anchor at any position:</translate>

* <translate><!--T:265--> The "anchor" [[<tvar name=1>help:Template</tvar>|template]], if it exists on your wiki, specified as <tvar name=2>{{tl|anchor}}</tvar>, offers a standardized method to create anchor points.</translate> <translate><!--T:266--> Place the template where you want, using the syntax <tvar name=2><nowiki>{{Anchor|Name_of_Anchor}}</nowiki></tvar>.</translate> <translate><!--T:267--> For instance, <nowiki>{{<tvar name=1>Anchor</tvar>|Description}}</nowiki> is placed in the "Description" column of the table below the "External links to internal pages" section.</translate> <translate><!--T:268--> Clicking on <tvar name=1>[[#Description]]</tvar> links to that anchor point created on the table.</translate> <translate><!--T:269--> The anchor is only visible via the source code.</translate>
* <translate><!--T:270--> Use the generic anchor tag <tvar name=1><code><nowiki><span id="anchor_name">some text</span></nowiki></code></tvar> with optional text for visible anchors.</translate> <translate><!--T:271--> For hidden anchors, omit the text.</translate> <translate><!--T:272--> To point to the anchor use <tvar name=1><code><nowiki>[[#anchor_name]]</nowiki></code></tvar>.</translate>
* <translate><!--T:273--> Avoid using manual HTML headings like <tvar name=1><code><nowiki><h2>Editing Instructions</h2></nowiki></code></tvar>.</translate> <translate><!--T:274--> This text serves as an <tvar name=1>anchor_name</tvar>.</translate>
* <translate><!--T:275--> In certain instances, adding an ID attribute similar to HTML within a Wiki-element is necessary.</translate> <translate><!--T:276--> Take, for instance, the table mentioned earlier, titled [[<tvar name=1>#External links to internal pages</tvar>|External links to internal pages]]:</translate>
:<code><nowiki>
border="1" class="wikitable" id="You type"
</nowiki></code>

* <translate><!--T:277--> A top of a page can be accessed using the reserved term <tvar name=1><code><nowiki>[[#top]]</nowiki></code></tvar>.</translate>

<translate>
<!--T:278-->
See also [[<tvar name=1>Special:MyLanguage/Help:Section#Linking sections using an arbitrary id</tvar>|Help:Section#Linking sections using an arbitrary ID]].

=== Using Linksearch anchors === <!--T:279-->

<!--T:280-->
As mentioned above, if external link style is used, e.g. <tvar name=1>[https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Help:Section#Linking_sections_using_an_arbitrary_id]</tvar>, we can use <tvar name=2>[[Special:Linksearch]]</tvar>: <tvar name=3>[https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Special:LinkSearch]</tvar>.
</translate>

<translate><!--T:281--> When using Linksearch, it's helpful to add leading zeros to numerical anchor names to prevent unintended matches.</translate>
<translate><!--T:282--> For example, instead of searching for "1", use "01" to avoid including "10".</translate>
<translate><!--T:283--> This practice is seen in [[w:Template:Current events header|Template:Current events header]].</translate>
<translate><!--T:284--> Similarly, if there are anchors like "a" and "ab", using "_a" can distinguish them in search results.</translate>

<translate>
=== Using <tvar name=1>anchorencode</tvar> === <!--T:285-->
</translate>
<translate><!--T:286--> The <tvar name=1><code>#anchorencode</code></tvar> parser function encodes input to use as an anchor.</translate>
<translate><!--T:287--> For example, to external link to <tvar name=1>[[#Using linksearch anchors]]</tvar> above, you would use <tvar name=2><code><nowiki>https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Help:Links#{{anchorencode:Using Linksearch anchors}}</nowiki></code></tvar>, which resolves to <tvar name=3>https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Help:Links#{{anchorencode:Using Linksearch anchors}}</tvar></translate>

<translate>
== Subpage feature == <!--T:288-->
</translate>
<translate><!--T:289--> MediaWiki has a [[<tvar name=1>mw:Special:MyLanguage/Help:subpages</tvar>|subpage]] feature that may or may not be active depending on the project and namespace.</translate>
<translate><!--T:290--> If it's activated, the following rules apply; otherwise, "A/b" is simply a standalone page with that name.</translate>

<translate><!--T:291--> A page's [[w:tree structure|tree structure]] is formed using forward slashes in page names: A/b is considered a subpage of A, making A the parent of A/b; additionally, A/b/c is a subpage of A/b; meanwhile, A/a, A/b, and A/c are categorized as sibling pages.</translate>

<translate><!--T:292--> The subpage body automatically displays links to all parent pages without needing specific wikitext.</translate>
<translate><!--T:293--> These links appear even if the parent page doesn't exist.</translate>
<translate><!--T:294--> However, if any ancestor page in the sequence is missing, the chain of links will stop before that point.</translate>
<translate><!--T:295--> Additionally, the capitalization of letters after the forward slash in the page name matters, meaning "<tvar name=1>/subpage</tvar>" and "<tvar name=2>/Subpage</tvar>" refer to different pages.</translate>

<translate>
<!--T:296-->
The functions, [[<tvar name=1>Special:MyLanguage/Help:What links here</tvar>|What links here]] and [[<tvar name=2>Special:MyLanguage/Help:Related changes</tvar>|Help:Related changes]] do not consider these automatically generated links.

<!--T:297-->
When the subpage feature is enabled within a namespace, any forward slash in a page's name automatically creates a subpage structure, regardless of whether it was intended or not.

<!--T:298-->
You can find a list of subpages using <tvar name=1>[[Special:PrefixIndex]]</tvar>.

=== Using variables === <!--T:299-->

<!--T:300-->
When utilizing the subpage feature within namespace A on page A:B/c/d, <tvar name=1><nowiki>{{BASEPAGENAME}}</nowiki></tvar> shows B/c while <tvar name=2><nowiki>{{SUBPAGENAME}}</nowiki></tvar> shows d.

=== Using relative links === <!--T:301-->

<!--T:302-->
Within a subpage hierarchy, you can utilize the following relative links:
</translate>

* <translate><!--T:303--> <tvar name=1><nowiki>[[../]]</nowiki></tvar> links to the parent page of the current subpage.</translate> <translate><!--T:304--> For example, on page A/b, it takes you to page A, and on page A/b/c, it directs you to page A/b.</translate>
* <translate><!--T:305--> <tvar name=1><nowiki>[[../../]]</nowiki></tvar> links to the grandparent page of the current subpage.</translate> <translate><!--T:306--> For example, on page A/b/c, it points to page A.</translate>
* <translate><!--T:307--> <tvar name=1><nowiki>[[../s]]</nowiki></tvar> links to a sibling page of the current subpage.</translate> <translate><!--T:308--> For example, on page A/b, it leads to page A/s.</translate>
* <translate><!--T:309--> <tvar name=1><nowiki>[[../../s]]</nowiki></tvar> links to an "uncle" page of the current subpage.</translate> <translate><!--T:310--> For example, on page A/b/c, it points to page A/s.</translate>
* <translate><!--T:311--> <tvar name=1><nowiki>[[/s]]</nowiki></tvar> links direct to a subpage.</translate> <translate><!--T:312--> On page A, it functions similarly to <tvar name=1><nowiki>[[A/s]]</nowiki></tvar>.</translate> <translate><!--T:313--> However, linking from a namespace with an enabled subpage feature to a main namespace page starting with <tvar name=1>"/"</tvar> requires a workaround: adding a colon before the page name.</translate>

<translate><!--T:314--> Relative links remain functional even when all pages within a hierarchy are renamed to reflect a change in the root's name, even if the root becomes a child of a new parent.</translate>
<translate><!--T:315--> Users with the appropriate permissions, such as administrators and those with the <tvar name=1><code>move-subpages</code></tvar> right, have the option to move both the main page and its subpages during a renaming process.</translate>

<translate><!--T:316--> Learn more about subpages at [[w:Wikipedia:Subpages|Subpages]].</translate>
<translate><!--T:317--> See examples at [[<tvar name=1>Special:MyLanguage/Help:Links/example</tvar>|Help:Links/example]] and [[<tvar name=2>Special:MyLanguage/Help:Links/example/example2</tvar>|Help:Links/example/example2]]</translate>

<translate>
=== Subpage activation === <!--T:318-->

<!--T:319-->
This feature is only enabled in namespaces specified in the <tvar name=1>{{wg|NamespacesWithSubpages}}</tvar> configuration setting, either its [[<tvar name=2>Special:MyLanguage/Manual:$wgNamespacesWithSubpages#Default value</tvar>|default namespaces]], or any additional namespaces set in <tvar name=4>{{ll|Manual:LocalSettings.php|LocalSettings.php}}</tvar>

== Character conversion == <!--T:320-->
</translate>
<translate><!--T:321--> The guidelines outlined in [[<tvar name=1>Special:MyLanguage/Manual:Page naming</tvar>|Manual:Page naming]] state that in wiki and interwiki links, conversions are made to [[<tvar name=2>Special:MyLanguage/Help:Special characters</tvar>|non-literal characters]] automatically.</translate>
<translate><!--T:322--> For example,"<tvar name=1><code><nowiki>[[Manual:Page%20naming]]</nowiki></code></tvar>" will display as "<tvar name=2>[[Manual:Page naming]]</tvar>".</translate>
<translate><!--T:323--> Conversely, external links operate oppositely; literal characters are transformed into non-literal characters.</translate>
<translate><!--T:324--> For example, browsers typically convert "<tvar name=1>.../wiki/!</tvar>" to "<tvar name=2>.../wiki/%21</tvar>".</translate>

<translate><!--T:325--> Applying a code like <tvar name=1>%70</tvar> to a redirect deactivates it, even though the link remains accessible from the redirect page.</translate>
<translate><!--T:326--> To ensure a successful redirect, the redirect page displays the canonical form of the target, unlike the preview page which shows the link in its regular format.</translate>

<translate>
== Miscellaneous == <!--T:327-->

=== Some additional effects of links === <!--T:328-->
</translate>
* {{ll|Help:Related changes|nsp=0}}
* <translate><!--T:329--> [[<tvar name=1>Special:MyLanguage/Help:What links here</tvar>|Backlink]]s, <tvar name=2>{{ll|Help:Linksearch|nsp=0}}</tvar></translate>
* <translate><!--T:330--> When you include a space after the pipe symbol (<tvar name=1><nowiki>[[main Page| ]]</nowiki></tvar>), the outcome can vary depending on the browser.</translate> <translate><!--T:331--> In some cases, it might only display a space ("&nbsp;"), without creating a clickable link.</translate> <translate><!--T:332--> However, it's still recognized as a link by the <tvar name=1><code>{{int|whatlinkshere}}</code></tvar> feature.</translate>

<translate>
=== "Hover box" on links === <!--T:333-->
</translate>
<translate><!--T:334--> In certain web browsers, when you place the cursor over a link, a tooltip may appear, displaying the content of the link's HTML title attribute.</translate>
<translate><!--T:335--> MediaWiki assigns different values to this attribute depending on the type of link: for internal wikilinks, it displays the '''page name''' and <tvar name=1><code>{{int|red-link-title|}}</code></tvar>, if the page does not exist; for interwiki links, it displays the page name with a prefix; and for external links, it displays the URL.</translate>

<translate><!--T:336--> The browser might also display similar information in its status bar, possibly showing which section it belongs to.</translate>

<translate><!--T:337--> Using a <tvar name=1>{{ll|Help:Links#Piped links|nsp=none}}</tvar>, even if it isn't clicked, can help clarify acronyms (like displaying "[[<tvar name=2>m:neutral point of view</tvar>|neutral point of view]]" as <tvar name=3>[[m:neutral point of view|NPOV]]</tvar>) or adding annotations.</translate>
<translate><!--T:338--> Hover boxes can also be created without links, you can customize the hover box content using markup like <tvar name=1><code><nowiki>[[Link title|<span title="hoverbox">Display text</span>]]</nowiki></code></tvar>.</translate>

<translate><!--T:339--> You cannot include a title attribute directly within the href element for '''external links'''.</translate>
<translate><!--T:340--> Nevertheless, you can achieve a similar outcome by using a span element instead, like this:</translate>
<code><nowiki>[http://www.example.com <span title="hover text on external link">www.example.com web site</span>]</nowiki></code> :<br />
[http://www.example.com <span title="hover text on external link">www.example.com web site</span>]

<translate>
